lub in New York rallied civic leaders, businessmen, artists, art collectors, and philanthropists to the cause. On April 13, 1870, The Metropolitan Museum of Art \",[\"$\",\"$L16\",\"703abcff2055\",{\"href\":{\"pathname\":\"/perspectives/today-in-met-history-april-13\"},\"className\":null,\"children\":[\"was incorporated\"]}],\", opening to the public in the Dodworth Building at 681 Fifth Avenue. On November 20 of that same year, the Museum \",[\"$\",\"$L16\",\"ae49015873b2\",{\"href\":{\"pathname\":\"/perspectives/this-weekend-in-met-history-november-21\"},\"className\":null,\"children\":[\"acquired its first object\"]}],\", a Roman sarcophagus. In 1871, 174 European paintings, including works by \",[\"$\",\"$L16\",\"0939a67b925b\",{\"href\":{\"pathname\":\"/essays/peter-paul-rubens-1577-1640-and-anthony-van-dyck-1599-1641-paintings\"},\"className\":null,\"children\":[\"Anthony van Dyck\"]}],\", \",[\"$\",\"$L16\",\"15db8c5a3346\",{\"href\":{\"pathname\":\"/essays/nicolas-poussin-1594-1665\"},\"className\":null,\"children\":[\"Nicolas Poussin\"]}],\", and \",[\"$\",\"$L16\",\"9e11ca81763b\",{\"href\":{\"pathname\":\"/essays/giovanni-battista-tiepolo-1696-1770\"},\"className\":null,\"children\":[\"Giovanni Battista Tiepolo\"]}],\", entered the collection.\"]}],[\"$\",\"p\",\"cb34e417d6ad\",{\"children\":[\"On March 30, 1880, after a \",[\"$\",\"$L16\",\"f762c0db9365\",{\"href\":{\"pathname\":\"/perspectives/today-in-met-history-march-1\"},\"className\":null,\"children\":[\"brief move to the Douglas Mansion\"]}],\" at 128 West 14th Street, the Museum opened to the public at its current site on Fifth Avenue and 82nd Street. The architects Calvert Vaux and Jacob Wrey Mould designed the initial Ruskinian Gothic structure, the west facade of which is still visible in the \",[\"$\",\"$L16\",\"35e8bcd97a65\",{\"href\":{\"pathname\":\"/departments/the-robert-lehman-collection\"},\"className\":null,\"children\":[\"Robert Lehman Wing\"]}],\". The building has since expanded greatly, and the various additions—built as early as 1888—now completely surround the original structure.\"]}],[\"$\",\"p\",\"542d941d9c72\",{\"children\":[\"The Museum's collection continued to grow throughout the rest of the 19th century. The 1874–76 purchase of the \",[\"$\",\"$L16\",\"ee164aa9100f\",{\"href\":{\"pathname\":\"/essays/the-cesnola-collection-at-the-metropolitan-museum-of-art\"},\"className\":null,\"children\":[\"Cesnola Collection of Cypriot art\"]}],\"—works dating from the Bronze Age to the end of the Roman period—helped to establish The Met's reputation as a major repository of classical antiquities. When the American painter John Kensett died in 1872, 38 of his canvases came to the Museum, and in 1889, the Museum acquired two works by \",[\"$\",\"$L16\",\"99423dd1e47e\",{\"href\":{\"pathname\":\"/essays/edouard-manet-1832-1883\"},\"className\":null,\"children\":[\"Édouard Manet\"]}],\".\"]}],[\"$\",\"p\",\"092ef96f9f0e\",{\"children\":[\"The Museum's Beaux-Arts Fifth Avenue facade and Great Hall, designed by the architect and founding Museum Trustee Richard Morris Hunt, opened to the public in December 1902. The \",\"$L28\",\" reported that at last New York had a neoclassical palace of art, \\\"one of the finest in the world, and the only public building in recent years which approaches in dignity and grandeur the museums of the old world.\\\"\"]}],\"$L29\",\"$L2a\",\"$L2b\",\"$L2c\",\"$L2d\",\"$L2e\",\"$L2f\",\"$L30\",\"$L31\",\"$L32\",\"$L33\",\"$L34\",\"$L35\",\"$L36\",\"$L37\",\"$L38\",\"$L39\",\"$L3a\",\"$L3b\",\"$L3c\",\"$L3d\",\"$L3e\",\"$L3f\",\"$L40\",\"$L41\",\"$L42\",\"$L43\",\"$L44\",\"$L45\",\"$L46\"]}],false]}]]}]\n"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"14:[\"$\",\"$L47\",null,{\"categories\":[{\"_key\":\"1fa1ba62b6be\",\"_type\":\"topLevelCategory\",\"links\":[{\"_key\":\"790af1953f42\",\"_type\":\"link\",\"title\":\"Plan Your Visit\",\"url\":\"/plan-your-visit\"},{\"_key\":\"f710cb3e852f\",\"_type\":\"link\",\"title\":\"Buy Ti