ab002fc62770\",{\"href\":{\"pathname\":\"/essays/auguste-renoir-1841-1919\"},\"className\":null,\"children\":[\"Auguste Renoir\"]}],\", and in 1910, The Met was the first public institution in the world to acquire a work of art by \",[\"$\",\"$L16\",\"a8eb6fd5a77c\",{\"href\":{\"pathname\":\"/essays/henri-matisse-1869-1954\"},\"className\":null,\"children\":[\"Henri Matisse\"]}],\". The ancient Egyptian \",[\"$\",\"$L16\",\"ba7d6186970a\",{\"className\":null,\"href\":\"https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/544227\",\"target\":\"_self\",\"rel\":\"noreferrer\",\"children\":[\"hippopotamus statuette\"]}],\" that is now the Museum's unofficial mascot, \\\"William,\\\" entered the collection in 1917. Today, almost all of the Museum's 30,000 ancient Egyptian objects, one of the largest collection of \",[\"$\",\"$L16\",\"e40108c7fa72\",{\"href\":{\"pathname\":\"/departments/egyptian-art\"},\"className\":null,\"children\":[\"Egyptian art\"]}],\" outside of Cairo, are on display. By 1979, the Museum owned five of the fewer than 35 known paintings by \",[\"$\",\"$L16\",\"639ceb9eb5a5\",{\"href\":{\"pathname\":\"/essays/johannes-vermeer-1632-1675\"},\"className\":null,\"children\":[\"Johannes Vermeer\"]}],\", and now The Met's 2,500 \",[\"$\",\"$L16\",\"52a3f7f1559d\",{\"href\":{\"pathname\":\"/departments/european-paintings-1250-1800\"},\"className\":null,\"children\":[\"European paintings\"]}],\" comprise one of the greatest such collections in the world. The \",[\"$\",\"$L16\",\"4c0ddfed006b\",{\"href\":{\"pathname\":\"/departments/the-american-wing\"},\"className\":null,\"children\":[\"American Wing\"]}],\" now houses the world's most comprehensive collection of American paintings, sculpture, and decorative arts.\"]}]\n"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"2a:[\"$\",\"p\",\"c0c34bf804da\",{\"children\":[\"Other major collections belonging to the Museum include \",[\"$\",\"$L16\",\"b07af6934d5b\",{\"href\":{\"pathname\":\"/departments/arms-and-armor\"},\"className\":null,\"children\":[\"arms and armor\"]}],\", the \",[\"$\",\"$L16\",\"cb1b34b7e69b\",{\"href\":{\"pathname\":\"/hubs/the-michael-c-rockefeller-wing\"},\"className\":null,\"children\":[\"arts of Africa, Oceania, and the Americas\"]}],\", \",[\"$\",\"$L16\",\"687998b205bc\",{\"href\":{\"pathname\":\"/departments/ancient-west-asian-art\"},\"className\":null,\"children\":[\"ancient West Asian art\"]}],\", \",[\"$\",\"$L16\",\"8c7c633c1fe6\",{\"href\":{\"pathname\":\"/departments/asian-art\"},\"className\":null,\"children\":[\"Asian art\"]}],\", \",[\"$\",\"$L16\",\"d917b8d26fdc\",{\"href\":{\"pathname\":\"/departments/the-costume-institute\"},\"className\":null,\"children\":[\"costume\"]}],\", \",[\"$\",\"$L16\",\"b4ff853675ac\",{\"href\":{\"pathname\":\"/departments/drawings-and-prints\"},\"className\":null,\"children\":[\"drawings and prints\"]}],\", \",[\"$\",\"$L16\",\"c4c2ad66b8ba\",{\"href\":{\"pathname\":\"/departments/european-sculpture-and-decorative-arts\"},\"className\":null,\"children\":[\"European sculpture and decorative arts\"]}],\", \",[\"$\",\"$L16\",\"cc672277409e\",{\"href\":{\"pathname\":\"/departments/greek-and-roman-art\"},\"className\":null,\"children\":[\"Greek and Roman art\"]}],\", \",[\"$\",\"$L16\",\"b674586a7844\",{\"href\":{\"pathname\":\"/departments/islamic-art\"},\"className\":null,\"children\":[\"Islamic art\"]}],\", \",[\"$\",\"$L16\",\"8a9a79ac2101\",{\"href\":{\"pathname\":\"/departments/medieval-art-and-the-cloisters\"},\"className\":null,\"children\":[\"medieval art\"]}],\", \",[\"$\",\"$L16\",\"762f6e52285e\",{\"href\":{\"pathname\":\"/departments/modern-and-contemporary-art\"},\"className\":null,\"children\":[\"modern and contemporary art\"]}],\", \",[\"$\",\"$L16\",\"fb7aafd3ee18\",{\"href\":{\"pathname\":\"/departments/musical-instruments\"},\"className\":null,\"children\":[\"musical instruments\"]}],\", \",[\"$\",\"$L16\",\"f42826e9bcc6\",{\"href\":{\"pathname\":\"/departments/photographs\"},\"className\":null,\"children\":[\"photographs\"]}],\", and the \",[\"$\",\"$L16\",\"8b4fc6be6e92\",{\"href\":{\"pathname\":\"/departments/the-robert-lehman-collection\"},\"className\":null,\"children\":[\"Robert Lehman Collection\"]}],\".\"]}]\n"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"2b:[\"$\",\"p\",\"f0d6fe1fa337\",{\"children\":[\"Today, tens of thousands of objects are on view at any given time in the Museum's two-million-square-foot building.\"]}]\n2c:[\"$\",\"p\",\"2bd5af58e512\",{\"children\":[\"A comprehensive architectural plan for the Museum by the architects Kevin Roche John Dinkeloo and Associates was approved in 1971 and completed in 1991. Among the additions to the Museum as part of the master plan are the Robert Lehman Wing (1975), which houses an extraordinary collection of Old Masters, as well as Impressionist and Post-Impressionist art; a wing to house the \",[\"$\",\"$L16\",\"29ec6397bdb9\",{\"className\":null,\"href\":\"https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/547802\",\"target\":\"_self\",\"rel\":\"noreferrer\",\"children\":[\"Temple of Dendur\"]}],\" (1978); The American Wing (1980), whose diverse collection includes 25 recently renovated period rooms; The Michael C. Rockefeller Wing (1982) displaying the arts of Africa, Oceania, and the Americas; the Lila Acheson Wallace Wing (1987) of modern and contemporary art; and the Henry R. Kravis Wing (1991) devoted to European sculpture and decorative arts from the Renaissance to the beginning of the 20th century.\"]}]\n2d:[\"$\",\"p\",\"e4d983d6181f\",{\"children\":[\"With the expansion of the building complete, The Met has continued to refine and reorganize its collection. In 1998, the Arts of Korea gallery opened to the public, completing a major suite of galleries devoted to the arts of Asia. The Ancient Near Eastern Art galleries reopened to the public in 1999 following a renovation. In 2007, several major projects at the south end of the building were completed, most notably the 15-year renovation and reinstallation of the entire suite of Greek and Roman Art galleries. Galleries for Oceanic and Native North American Art also opened in 2007, as well as the new Galleries for Nineteenth- and Early Twentieth-Century Paintings and Sculpture and the Ruth and Harold D. Uris Center for Education.\"]}]\n2e:[\"$\",\"p\",\"f7c4c7c70751\",{\"children\":[\"On November 1, 2011, the Museum's New Galleries for the Art of the Arab Lands, Turkey, Iran, Central Asia, and Later South Asia opened to the public. On the north side of the Museum, The Met's New American Wing Galleries for Paintings, Sculpture, and Decorative Arts reopened on January 16, 2012, signaling the completion of the third and final phase of The American Wing's renovation.\"]}]\n2f:[\"$\",\"p\",\"0b0cb0311745\",{\"children\":[\"In May 2021, The Met installed a plaque on the Fifth Avenue facade \",[\"$\",\"$L16\",\"28dd349c1368\",{\"href\":{\"pathname\":\"/press-releases/land-acknowledgment-2021-news\"},\"className\":null,\"children\":[\"recognizing Lenapehoking\"]}],\", the homeland of the Indigenous Lenape peoples.\"]}]\n30:[\"$\",\"p\",\"c41649caa4c9\",{\"children\":[\"\"]}]\n31:[\"$\",\"h2\",\"0fa7aaad6fe3\",{\"className\":\"blocks-module-scss-module__chXROq__h2\",\"children\":[\"The Met Cloisters\"]}]\n"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"32:[\"$\",\"div\",\"a12b3a2b4391\",{\"className\":\"image-module-scss-module__Cc8UIW__imageWrapper\",\"children\":[\"$\",\"figure\",null,{\"style\":{\"maxWidth\":\"100%\"},\"className\":\"image-module-scss-module__Cc8UIW__figure\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"$L4a\",null,{\"alt\":\"A medieval stone building with a tall tower on the right in a forest landscape, of trees, brush, and a cloudy sky. The large river is visible behind the building in this in black and white photograph. \",\"sizes\":\"(max-width: 960px) 85vw, 1200px\",\"image\":{\"_key\":\"a12b3a2b4391\",\"_resolved\":true,\"_type\":\"image\",\"alt\":\"A medieval stone building with a tall tower on the right in a forest landsc